    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Default and intuitive shortcuts play an important role in usability of any software product. It looks like `nvim` maintains compatibility with `vim` in areas that could behave better. Like editing multiple files.\r\n\r\n- `nvim --version`: v0.4.4\r\n\r\nOpen multiple files.\r\n```\r\nnvim *.haml\r\n```\r\nFirst problem is that there are no shortcuts for closing current file or moving to next or previous one.\r\n\r\nThe second problem is that commands for managing open files are inconsistent.\r\n`:n` - `next file`, but\r\n`:p` - is `:print`, and one needs `:prev`\r\n`:q` - warns about files left to edit, but leaves current file visible\r\n`:c` - is `:change:` and not `:close` (I have no idea how often `:change` is used and what for)\r\n`:close` - shows message \"can not close last window\"\r\n\r\n`:bd` - I would say that 355 StackOverflow upvotes is bad metric for an intuitive usability feature https://stackoverflow.com/questions/256204/close-file-without-quitting-vim-application\r\n\r\nOpening files.\r\n`:o` - doesn't `:open`, but just lists `:oldfiles`\r\n`:open` - not an editor command\r\n\r\nHonestly, I don't know how add a new file to the list of files already open.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nNeovim advertises itself as being focused on usability, so I am curious what is it future take on that user experience?",
